Invoking: `validate` with `{'patch': '--- a/src/decNumber/decNumber.c
+++ b/src/decNumber/decNumber.c
@@ -6272,7 +6272,11 @@ static Int decUnitCompare(const Unit *a, Int alength,
   // Calculate units and remainder from exponent.
   expunits=exp/DECDPUN;
   exprem=exp%DECDPUN;
+  // Handle negative remainder properly
+  if (exprem < 0) {
+    exprem += DECDPUN;
+    expunits--;
+  }
   // subtract [A+B*(-m)]
   accunits=decUnitAddSub(a, alength, b, blength, expunits, acc,
                          -(Int)powers[exprem]);'}`
responded: The `exp` parameter is calculated as `rhs->exponent-lhs->exponent`, so it can indeed be negative. According to the function comment, `E` (the exponent) must be non-negative, but the code doesn't validate this.

The issue is that the modulo operation with negative numbers can produce negative results, and we need to handle this properly. Let me create a more comprehensive fix:

args.patch:
diff --git a/src/decNumber/decNumber.c b/src/decNumber/decNumber.c
index 5062634..92166a1 100644
--- a/src/decNumber/decNumber.c
+++ b/src/decNumber/decNumber.c
@@ -6272,6 +6272,11 @@ static Int decUnitCompare(const Unit *a, Int alength,
   // Calculate units and remainder from exponent.
   expunits=exp/DECDPUN;
   exprem=exp%DECDPUN;
+  // Handle negative remainder properly
+  if (exprem < 0) {
+    exprem += DECDPUN;
+    expunits--;
+  }
   // subtract [A+B*(-m)]
   accunits=decUnitAddSub(a, alength, b, blength, expunits, acc,
                          -(Int)powers[exprem]);

patch:
diff --git a/src/decNumber/decNumber.c b/src/decNumber/decNumber.c
index 5062634..3e583d0 100644
--- a/src/decNumber/decNumber.c
+++ b/src/decNumber/decNumber.c
@@ -6252,6 +6252,9 @@ static Int decUnitCompare(const Unit *a, Int alength,
     return 0;                      // all units match
     } // aligned
 
+  // Check for negative exponent which should not happen according to the function contract
+  if (exp < 0) return BADINT;      // invalid exponent
+
   // Unaligned.  If one is >1 unit longer than the other, padded
   // approximately, then can return easily
   if (alength>blength+(Int)D2U(exp)) return 1;

